cs.CL, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.IR, cs.NE 

This paper is likely to belong to the category of Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) as it deals with the task of learning distributed word vector representations and their composition to form phrase embeddings. It also involves experiments related to word and phrase similarity tasks as well as syntactic tasks like dependency parsing. 

It could also belong to the category of Machine Learning (cs.LG) as it proposes a learning procedure for the skip-gram model that incorporates a phrase-compositionality function. 

Additionally, it could be categorized under Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) as it involves the task of learning representations for natural language processing tasks. 

Information Retrieval (cs.IR) could also be a possible category as the paper deals with the task of learning distributed representations for words and phrases, which can be useful in information retrieval tasks. 

Finally, Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) could be another possible category as the paper proposes a joint model for learning distributed representations using neural networks.
